hands_on_practices.solution:
1. For BCC, nearest‐neighbor distance is along the body diagonal: 
$$\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}a_{BCC}=2r\quad\Longrightarrow\quad a_{BCC}=\frac{4r}{\sqrt{3}}.$$
The cubic cell contains 2 atoms, so
$$V_{BCC}=\frac{a_{BCC}^3}{2}
=\frac{1}{2}\Bigl(\frac{4r}{\sqrt{3}}\Bigr)^3
=\frac{32\,r^3}{3^{3/2}}.$$

2. For FCC, nearest‐neighbor distance lies along the face diagonal:
$$\frac{a_{FCC}}{\sqrt{2}}=2r\quad\Longrightarrow\quad a_{FCC}=2\sqrt{2}\,r.$$
The cell contains 4 atoms, so
$$V_{FCC}=\frac{a_{FCC}^3}{4}
=\frac{(2\sqrt{2}\,r)^3}{4}
=4\sqrt{2}\,r^3.$$

3. The fractional change is
$$\frac{\Delta V}{V_{FCC}}
=\frac{V_{FCC}-V_{BCC}}{V_{FCC}}
=\frac{4\sqrt{2}\,r^3-\frac{32\,r^3}{3^{3/2}}}{4\sqrt{2}\,r^3}
=1-\frac{8}{3\sqrt{6}}
=\frac{9-4\sqrt{6}}{9}.$$
